      "source": [
        "## 3. Quick Look at the Data\n",
        "\n",
        "Before modeling we run two basic checks that we always did in class before training: how many **missing values** each column has, and whether there are any **duplicate rows**. Duplicates are removed so the model is not trained on the same observation twice."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "e4e98f7a",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "e4e98f7a"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "print(\"Missing values per column:\")\n",
        "print(df.isnull().sum())\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nDuplicate rows:\", df.duplicated().sum())\n",
        "\n",
        "df = df.drop_duplicates()\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "6682c1a5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6682c1a5"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 4. Leakage Prevention — Drop the columns that give away the answer\n",
        "\n",
        "**Data leakage** = using information that the model would not actually have *before* making a prediction. The columns below either *are* the target or are directly derived from the same-day arrival outcome, so they would reveal the answer during training. They are removed from the feature set entirely.\n",
        "\n",
        "We also drop `Date` itself — we already have `year`, `month`, `weekday`, `is_weekend`, and `season` as separate columns, so the raw date string isn't needed as a feature."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "70a9e78d",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "70a9e78d"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "leakage_cols = [\n",
        "    \"target_delay_category\",\n",
        "    \"arr_delay_min\",\n",
        "    \"Avg Arrival Schedule Delay\",\n",
        "    \"Arrival Punctuality %\",\n",
        "    \"arr_punctuality_pct\",\n",
        "    \"Date\",\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "leakage_cols = [c for c in leakage_cols if c in df.columns]\n",
        "df = df.drop(columns=leakage_cols)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Dropped columns:\", leakage_cols)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "9a106fd7",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9a106fd7"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 5. Target Definitions and Feature Matrix\n",
        "\n",
        "This project predicts delay using **two related targets**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- `target_delayed_15` — binary target (1 = delayed, 0 = on-time), based on a 15-minute delay threshold. This is the target for **Stage 1 (Classification)**.\n",
        "- `target_delay_minutes` — the average arrival delay in minutes for the airport-day. This is the target for **Stage 2 (Regression)**.\n",
        "\n",
        "Everything else becomes our feature matrix `X`, exactly like the `medical_data.csv` example from class (`X = df.drop(columns='Additional_charges')`)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "6f5e6ffd",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6f5e6ffd"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "y_class = df[\"target_delayed_15\"]\n",
        "y_reg   = df[\"target_delay_minutes\"]\n",
        "\n",
        "X = df.drop(columns=[\"target_delayed_15\", \"target_delay_minutes\"])\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Feature matrix shape:\", X.shape)\n",
        "X.head()\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "2ad10051",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2ad10051"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 6. Train / Test Split\n",
        "\n",
        "A plain random 80/20 split with `random_state` set so the results are reproducible — the same kind of split used in every example in the slides. The model is trained on the training data and evaluated on the testing data, which it has never seen during training."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "a30df977",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a30df977"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "X_train, X_test, y_class_train, y_class_test, y_reg_train, y_reg_test = train_test_split(\n",
        "    X, y_class, y_reg, test_size=0.2, random_state=42\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Train rows:\", X_train.shape[0])\n",
        "print(\"Test rows: \", X_test.shape[0])\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "2b34540b",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2b34540b"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 7. Preprocessing Pipeline\n",
        "\n",
        "One shared `ColumnTransformer` handles both numeric and categorical columns and is reused by both stages:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Numeric features:** `SimpleImputer(strategy=\"median\")` → `StandardScaler()`\n",
        "- **Categorical features:** `SimpleImputer(strategy=\"most_frequent\")` → `OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown=\"ignore\")`\n",
        "\n",
        "`handle_unknown=\"ignore\"` protects against categories that appear in the test set but were never seen during training (e.g., a new airport). The preprocessor is fit only on the training data; the test data is transformed using the rules learned from training."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "546f3113",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "546f3113"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "num_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(\"number\").columns\n",
        "cat_cols = X_train.select_dtypes(\"object\").columns\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Numeric columns:\", list(num_cols))\n",
        "print(\"Categorical columns:\", list(cat_cols))\n",
        "\n",
        "impute_median = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"median\")\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "num_pipe = make_pipeline(impute_median, scaler)\n",
        "\n",
        "impute_mode = SimpleImputer(strategy=\"most_frequent\")\n",
        "ohe = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown=\"ignore\")\n",
        "cat_pipe = make_pipeline(impute_mode, ohe)\n",
        "\n",
        "preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([\n",
        "    (\"numeric\", num_pipe, num_cols),\n",
        "    (\"categorical\", cat_pipe, cat_cols),\n",
        "], remainder=\"drop\", verbose_feature_names_out=False)\n",
        "\n",
        "preprocessor\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "acf080aa",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "acf080aa"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Stage 1: Logistic Regression — Delay Classification\n",
        "\n",
        "### Machine Learning Model\n",
        "\n",
        "For Stage 1, we selected **Logistic Regression** as our machine learning model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Logistic Regression is a classification algorithm that predicts whether something belongs to one of two classes (binary classification). In our case, it predicts whether an airport-day will be **delayed (1)** or **on-time (0)**.\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike Linear Regression which outputs a continuous number, Logistic Regression uses the **Sigmoid function** to map the output to a probability between 0 and 1. If the probability is above 0.5, the model predicts \"delayed\"; otherwise it predicts \"on-time\".\n",
        "\n",
        "Before training, the dataset was preprocessed by:\n",
        "- Handling missing values\n",
        "- Encoding categorical variables using `OneHotEncoder`\n",
        "- Scaling numerical features using `StandardScaler`\n",
        "- Removing leakage columns (see Section 4)\n",
        "\n",
        "The dataset was then split randomly into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "49f5afca",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "49f5afca"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 8. Model Training — Logistic Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "**Target:** `target_delayed_15` (1 = delayed, 0 = on-time)\n",
        "**Model:** `LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)` — `max_iter=1000` is set so the solver has enough iterations to converge on the full feature set."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "a040c1f2",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a040c1f2"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "clf_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)\n",
        "clf_pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor, clf_model)\n",
        "\n",
        "clf_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_class_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "clf_test_pred = clf_pipeline.predict(X_test)\n",
        "print(\"Logistic Regression trained.\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "44b256df",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "44b256df"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 9. Look at the Model Parameters\n",
        "\n",
        "Same as in class: after scaling, each numeric coefficient tells us how much the **log-odds of being delayed** change when that feature increases by **one standard deviation**, holding everything else constant.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Positive coefficient → pushes the prediction toward **delayed**.\n",
        "- Negative coefficient → pushes the prediction toward **on-time**.\n",
        "- Larger absolute value → stronger effect on the prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "For one-hot encoded categorical features (like specific airports or countries), the coefficient shows whether that particular category systematically runs later or earlier than the average."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "2ab18e63",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2ab18e63"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "feature_names = clf_pipeline.named_steps[\"columntransformer\"].get_feature_names_out()\n",
        "b_0 = clf_model.intercept_[0].round(2)\n",
        "b_i = clf_model.coef_[0].round(2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"intercept (bias): {b_0}\")\n",
        "for name, weight in zip(feature_names, b_i):\n",
        "    print(f\"{name:30s} weight = {weight:+.2f}\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "349b1fbb",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "349b1fbb"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 10. Evaluate Stage 1 on the Test Set\n",
        "\n",
        "The performance of the Logistic Regression model was evaluated using the four classification metrics from class:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Accuracy** — what percentage of all predictions were correct?\n",
        "- **Precision** — out of all airport-days predicted as delayed, how many were actually delayed?\n",
        "- **Recall** — out of all airport-days that were actually delayed, how many did the model correctly catch?\n",
        "- **F1-score** — the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall, useful when classes are imbalanced.\n",
        "\n",
        "We also display the **confusion matrix** and the full **classification report**.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What these numbers mean:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Accuracy** → the percentage of airport-days the model classified correctly out of the total test set.\n",
        "- **Precision** → when the model predicts \"delayed\", how often is it actually right? A higher value means fewer false alarms.\n",
        "- **Recall** → out of all airport-days that were *actually* delayed, how many did the model catch? A higher value means fewer missed delays.\n",
        "- **F1-score** → a balanced combination of Precision and Recall. Useful here because the classes are imbalanced (more on-time days than delayed days)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "8f28c394",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8f28c394"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "accuracy  = accuracy_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
        "precision = precision_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
        "recall    = recall_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
        "f1        = f1_score(y_class_test, clf_test_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Accuracy:  {accuracy:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Precision: {precision:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Recall:    {recall:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"F1-score:  {f1:.3f}\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "40d52d01",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "40d52d01"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_class_test, clf_test_pred);\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "787e3ff5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "787e3ff5"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "print(classification_report(y_class_test, clf_test_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "7875377c",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7875377c"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 11. Overfit / Underfit Check — Stage 1\n",
        "\n",
        "Same approach as the \"students pass/not pass\" example from class: evaluate the model on the **training** data too, then compare with the test data.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Underfit (High Bias):** the model performs poorly on both train and test data.\n",
        "- **Overfit (High Variance):** the model performs well on train data but significantly worse on test data.\n",
        "- **Good model:** the model performs well on both, with no significant gap."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "b4442055",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b4442055"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "clf_train_pred = clf_pipeline.predict(X_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Classification report: Training data\")\n",
        "print(classification_report(y_class_train, clf_train_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Classification report: Test data\")\n",
        "print(classification_report(y_class_test, clf_test_pred, target_names=[\"On-time\", \"Delayed\"]))\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "1da7711c",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1da7711c"
      },
      "source": [
        "**How to interpret the result:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- If Train Accuracy ≈ Test Accuracy and both are acceptable → **Good model, no overfit or underfit.**\n",
        "- If Train Accuracy >> Test Accuracy (significant gap) → **Overfit (High Variance).**\n",
        "- If both Train and Test Accuracy are low → **Underfit (High Bias).**\n",
        "\n",
        "**My interpretation:** *(fill this in after running the cells above on your real data — compare the train vs test accuracy / F1 and say whether you see overfitting, underfitting, or neither.)*"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "d142c7b9",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "d142c7b9"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# Stage 2: Linear Regression — Predicting Delay Minutes\n",
        "\n",
        "### Machine Learning Model\n",
        "\n",
        "For Stage 2, we use **Linear Regression** to predict the number of delay minutes (`target_delay_minutes`).\n",
        "\n",
        "Linear Regression is a supervised learning algorithm used to **predict a continuous value** (a number). It works by finding the best-fit straight line through the data that minimizes the prediction error.\n",
        "\n",
        "The general equation of Linear Regression is:\n",
        "\n",
        "**ŷ = β₀ + β₁×x₁ + β₂×x₂ + ... + βₙ×xₙ**\n",
        "\n",
        "Where:\n",
        "- **ŷ** is the predicted delay in minutes\n",
        "- **x₁, x₂, ...xₙ** are the input features\n",
        "- **β₀** is the intercept (bias)\n",
        "- **β₁, β₂, ...βₙ** are the coefficients (weights) learned by the model\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike Stage 1 which answers *\"will there be a delay?\"*, this model answers *\"how many minutes will the delay be?\"*\n",
        "\n",
        "The same feature set, preprocessing pipeline, and 80/20 split from Stage 1 are reused here."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "694daee7",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "694daee7"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 12. Model Training — Linear Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "**Target:** `target_delay_minutes` (continuous value — minutes)\n",
        "**Model:** `LinearRegression`"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "ab6d448e",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ab6d448e"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "reg_model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "reg_pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor, reg_model)\n",
        "\n",
        "reg_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_reg_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "reg_test_pred = reg_pipeline.predict(X_test)\n",
        "print(\"Linear Regression trained.\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "db76b891",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "db76b891"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 13. Look at the Model Parameters\n",
        "\n",
        "For the Linear Regression model, each coefficient represents how many **minutes the predicted delay changes** when that feature increases by one standard deviation, with all other features held constant.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Positive coefficient → pushes the predicted delay **up**.\n",
        "- Negative coefficient → pushes the predicted delay **down**.\n",
        "- The intercept (`β₀`) is the baseline predicted delay when all standardized features are at their mean."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "9d5ce4ef",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9d5ce4ef"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "feature_names_reg = reg_pipeline.named_steps[\"columntransformer\"].get_feature_names_out()\n",
        "b_0_reg = reg_model.intercept_.round(2)\n",
        "b_i_reg = reg_model.coef_.round(2)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"intercept (bias): {b_0_reg}\")\n",
        "for name, weight in zip(feature_names_reg, b_i_reg):\n",
        "    print(f\"{name:30s} weight = {weight:+.2f}\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "83e99c17",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "83e99c17"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 14. Evaluate Stage 2 on the Test Set\n",
        "\n",
        "The Linear Regression model was evaluated using the four regression metrics from class, packaged in a small helper function (same style we used in the lecture) so we can reuse it for train vs test:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **MAE (Mean Absolute Error)** — the average absolute difference between predicted and actual delay minutes. Easy to interpret: \"on average, the model is off by X minutes.\"\n",
        "- **MSE (Mean Squared Error)** — the average of squared errors; larger errors are penalized more.\n",
        "- **RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)** — the square root of MSE, back in the same units (minutes). Useful for detecting cases where the model makes very large mistakes.\n",
        "- **R² Score (Coefficient of Determination)** — measures how much of the variation in delay minutes is explained by the model. Ranges from 0 to 1; closer to 1 is better.\n",
        "\n",
        "| R² Range | Meaning |\n",
        "|---|---|\n",
        "| 0.9 – 1.0 | Excellent fit |\n",
        "| 0.7 – 0.9 | Good fit |\n",
        "| 0.5 – 0.7 | Moderate fit |\n",
        "| < 0.5 | Weak — model is underperforming |"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "a81885d0",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "a81885d0"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def regression_metrics(y_true, y_pred, label=\"\"):\n",
        "    mae  = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)\n",
        "    mse  = mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)\n",
        "    rmse = mse ** 0.5\n",
        "    r2   = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "    print(\"-\" * 50)\n",
        "    print(f\"Regression Metrics: {label}\")\n",
        "    print(\"-\" * 50)\n",
        "    print(f\"- MAE  = {mae:,.3f}\")\n",
        "    print(f\"- MSE  = {mse:,.3f}\")\n",
        "    print(f\"- RMSE = {rmse:,.3f}\")\n",
        "    print(f\"- R^2  = {r2:,.3f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "regression_metrics(y_reg_test, reg_test_pred, label=\"Test Data\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "631cc198",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "631cc198"
      },
      "source": [
        "## 15. Overfit / Underfit Check — Stage 2\n",
        "\n",
        "Same idea as Example 1/2 in class: compute the metrics on train data too, then compare with the test data.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Underfit (High Bias):** high error on both train and test data.\n",
        "- **Overfit (High Variance):** low error on train data but significantly higher error on test data.\n",
        "- **Good model:** similar error on both train and test, with acceptable values."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "5eeca297",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5eeca297"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "reg_train_pred = reg_pipeline.predict(X_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "regression_metrics(y_reg_train, reg_train_pred, label=\"Training Data\")\n",
        "print()\n",
        "regression_metrics(y_reg_test, reg_test_pred, label=\"Test Data\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
